'she ideal of democracy is as imperishable as the ideal of theocracy, and I have often observed this to be true in the minds of men who, having formed some fantastic idea of a democracy or of a divine government‚ vent passionate denunciation upon the one or the other. For such denunciations are always based on an ideal of one or the other which they declare too good to be realised. Even those strongly imbued with the belief in paternal government as more than a temporary expedient will not for a moment deny the truth of the old adage, ‘⁶ He that ruleth his spirit is the greatest conqueror’'; and thus as the object of paternal education must always be to make men fit to govern themselves, and no one will deny that the man who can govern himself does not need to be ruled and so must have a voice in the corporate government from which he and his children receive good or ill. “There is none good but God '' is also a belief that must ultimately lead the reason to advocate equality of outward privilege and opportunity among men3 and equality of outward privilege and opportunity among men cannot long be the rule in any community unless a standard of good is set up and held to be sacrosanct‚ and it is difficult to see how this could differ in any essential respect from divine law.
